back:
X_L = \omega L = 2\pi f L

\omega = \text{angular frequency (rad/s)}
L = \text{inductance (H)}
f = \text{frequency (Hz)}

Units: ohm (\Omega)

**Behaviour:** X_L \propto f — increases linearly with frequency

At DC (f = 0): X_L = 0 (pure wire)
At high f: X_L \to \infty (blocks AC)

X_C = \frac{1}{\omega C} = \frac{1}{2\pi f C}

\omega = \text{angular frequency (rad/s)}
C = \text{capacitance (F)}

Units: ohm (\Omega)

**Behaviour:** X_C \propto \frac{1}{f} — decreases as frequency increases

At DC (f = 0): X_C \to \infty (blocks DC)
At high f: X_C \to 0 (passes AC freely)

Z = \sqrt{R^2 + (X_L - X_C)^2}

Z = \sqrt{R^2 + \left(\omega L - \frac{1}{\omega C}\right)^2}

**Special cases:**
- Series RL: Z = \sqrt{R^2 + \omega^2 L^2}
- Series RC: Z = \sqrt{R^2 + \frac{1}{\omega^2 C^2}}
- At resonance: Z_{min} = R

Units: ohm (\Omega)

\tan\theta = \frac{X_L - X_C}{R} = \frac{\omega L - \frac{1}{\omega C}}{R}

\theta = \tan^{-1}\!\left(\frac{X_L - X_C}{R}\right)

**Sign convention:**
- \theta > 0: X_L > X_C \Rightarrow \text{inductive, V leads I}
- \theta < 0: X_C > X_L \Rightarrow \text{capacitive, I leads V}
- \theta = 0: X_L = X_C \Rightarrow \text{resonance, V and I in phase}

\text{Condition: } X_L = X_C \Rightarrow \omega_0 L = \frac{1}{\omega_0 C}

\omega_0 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{LC}} \quad \text{(rad/s)}

\nu_0 = \frac{1}{2\pi\sqrt{LC}} \quad \text{(Hz)}

\text{At resonance:}
\quad Z = R \text{ (minimum)}
\quad I_{max} = \frac{V_{rms}}{R}
\quad \cos\theta = 1 \text{ (power factor = 1)}

Q = \frac{\omega_0 L}{R} = \frac{1}{\omega_0 CR} = \frac{1}{R}\sqrt{\frac{L}{C}}

**Physical meaning:**
Q = \frac{\text{resonant frequency}}{\text{bandwidth}} = \frac{\nu_0}{\Delta\nu}

**Voltage magnification at resonance:**
V_L = V_C = Q \times V_{source}

**Higher Q:** sharper resonance peak, more selective circuit

\Delta\omega = \frac{R}{L} \quad \text{(rad/s)}

\Delta\nu = \frac{R}{2\pi L} \quad \text{(Hz)}

\text{Half-power frequencies: } \omega_1, \omega_2 \text{ where } I = \frac{I_{max}}{\sqrt{2}}

\Delta\omega = \omega_2 - \omega_1

\text{Relation to Q-factor: } Q = \frac{\omega_0}{\Delta\omega} = \frac{\nu_0}{\Delta\nu}

P_{av} = V_{rms}\, I_{rms}\cos\theta

P_{av} = I_{rms}^2\, R

P_{av} = \frac{V_{rms}^2 R}{Z^2}

**Special cases:**
- Resistor only: P = I_{rms}^2 R
- Pure inductor: P = 0
- Pure capacitor: P = 0
- At resonance: P_{max} = \frac{V_{rms}^2}{R}

\cos\theta = \text{power factor}

\text{Active (watt-full) component: } I_{rms}\cos\theta

\text{Wattless (reactive) component: } I_{rms}\sin\theta

**Power contribution:**
P = V_{rms} \cdot (I_{rms}\cos\theta) \quad \leftarrow \text{only active part contributes}

P_{wattless\ component} = 0

\text{Arises from pure L or C — energy is stored and returned,}
\text{not dissipated. Net power = 0.}

\text{Angular frequency: } \omega = \frac{1}{\sqrt{LC}}

\text{Frequency: } \nu = \frac{1}{2\pi\sqrt{LC}}

\text{Time period: } T = 2\pi\sqrt{LC}

**Energy oscillation:**
U_C = \frac{q^2}{2C} \quad (\text{electric, max when } I = 0)
U_L = \frac{1}{2}LI^2 \quad (\text{magnetic, max when } q = 0)

U_C + U_L = \frac{q_0^2}{2C} = \text{constant (ideal LC)}

\frac{1}{Z} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{R^2} + \left(\frac{1}{X_C} - \frac{1}{X_L}\right)^2}

\frac{1}{Z} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{R^2} + \left(\omega C - \frac{1}{\omega L}\right)^2}

\text{Resonance condition: } I_C = I_L
\Rightarrow \frac{1}{X_C} = \frac{1}{X_L} \Rightarrow \omega_0 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{LC}}

\text{At resonance: } Z = R \text{ (maximum)}, \ I = I_R \text{ (minimum)}

\text{Instantaneous current: } I = I_0 \sin(\omega t + \phi)
\text{Instantaneous voltage: } V = V_0 \sin(\omega t + \phi)

\omega = 2\pi\nu = \frac{2\pi}{T}

\text{where:}
\quad I_0, V_0 = \text{peak (amplitude) values}
\quad \omega = \text{angular frequency (rad/s)}
\quad \nu = \text{frequency (Hz)}
\quad T = \text{time period (s)}
\quad \phi = \text{initial phase angle}

**(A) Z = 5 Ω, inductive**

**Solution:**
Z = \sqrt{R^2 + (X_L - X_C)^2}
Z = \sqrt{3^2 + (8 - 4)^2} = \sqrt{9 + 16} = \sqrt{25} = 5\,\Omega

Since X_L > X_C \Rightarrow \text{net reactance is positive} \Rightarrow \text{circuit is inductive}

\theta = \tan^{-1}\!\left(\frac{4}{3}\right) = 53° \quad \text{(V leads I)}

front:
In an AC circuit, the voltage applied is V = V_0\sin\omega t and the resulting current is I = I_0\sin\!\left(\omega t - \frac{\pi}{2}\right). The average power consumed is:

(A) \frac{V_0 I_0}{2}
(B) \frac{V_0 I_0}{\sqrt{2}}
(C) V_0 I_0
(D) Zero

A series LCR circuit has L = 0.5 H, C = 1 μF, R = 3 Ω. The quality factor Q of the circuit is:

(A) 111
(B) \frac{1000}{3}
(C) 333
(D) \frac{500}{3}

back:
**(B) \frac{1000}{3} \approx 333.3**

**Solution:**
\omega_0 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{LC}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{0.5 \times 10^{-6}}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{5 \times 10^{-7}}} \approx 1414\text{ rad/s}

Q = \frac{\omega_0 L}{R} = \frac{1414 \times 0.5}{3} \approx \frac{707}{3} \approx 236

Alternatively using Q = \frac{1}{R}\sqrt{\frac{L}{C}} = \frac{1}{3}\sqrt{\frac{0.5}{10^{-6}}} = \frac{1}{3}\sqrt{5 \times 10^5} = \frac{\sqrt{500000}}{3} \approx \frac{707}{3} \approx 235.6

**Key formula to remember:** Q = \frac{1}{R}\sqrt{\frac{L}{C}}

**(B) 242 W**

**Solution:**
At resonance: \cos\theta = 1 and Z = R = 200\,\Omega

I_{rms} = \frac{V_{rms}}{R} = \frac{220}{200} = 1.1\,\text{A}

P = I_{rms}^2 \times R = (1.1)^2 \times 200 = 1.21 \times 200 = 242\,\text{W}

**Alternative:** P = \frac{V_{rms}^2}{R} = \frac{220^2}{200} = \frac{48400}{200} = 242\,\text{W}

**(C) 20 A**

**Solution:**
\frac{I_p}{I_s} = \frac{N_s}{N_p} = \frac{10}{1} = 10

I_p = 10 \times I_s = 10 \times 2 = 20\,\text{A}

**Verification (energy conservation):**
V_s = 10 \times 230 = 2300\,\text{V}
P_{input} = 230 \times 20 = 4600\,\text{W}
P_{output} = 2300 \times 2 = 4600\,\text{W} \checkmark

Step-up in voltage → step-down in current (ideal transformer).

